question27:
The eUTXO model is probably its most significant technical asset. 
Developers who take the time to understand it often find it enables more predictable and secure smart contract behavior, which is crucial for financial applications where bugs can be catastrophic.
question28:
Documentation is sometimes scattered across different sources, libraries may have inconsistent maintenance, and there isnt always a clear blessed path for common tasks. Developers coming from web2 or other ecosystems often find themselves needing to piece together workflows from multiple tools and sources rather than having a cohesive, well-integrated development environment.
The learning curve is also steep, which compounds the tooling issues. The eUTXO model requires a different mental model than account-based systems, Plutus requires understanding functional programming concepts, and there arent as many tutorials, courses, or Stack Overflow answers to fall back on when you get stuck. This means developers spend more time figuring out how to do things rather than actually building, which can be frustrating and slow down adoption.
The smaller ecosystem size creates a chicken-and-egg problem too. Fewer developers means fewer libraries, frameworks, and third-party tools, which means its harder to build quickly, which discourages more developers from joining. While the community is passionate and helpful, you cant always find someone whos solved your exact problem before, whereas in larger ecosystems someone has almost certainly hit the same issue and documented the solution.
Infrastructure tooling like testing frameworks, local development environments, and debugging tools also lag behind more mature chains. Getting a smooth local development workflow set up can be more involved than it should be.
